{
  "texts": [
    "Using cork and other biobased materials as construction materials can facilitate energy conservation efforts and carbon emissions, thereby mitigating greenhouse gas emissions and combatting climate change (Le et al. 2023).",
    "Rabbat et al. (2022) also discovered that the expected energy recovery from bio-based insulation waste by 2050 offers significant environmental and economic benefits, and the practice of energy recovery from such waste could prevent the emission of approximately 312,771 tons of carbon dioxide equivalent.",
    "This substantial reduction in greenhouse gas emissions represents a significant step toward mitigating climate change impacts.",
    "Secondly, biomaterials have the potential to enhance indoor environmental quality under their natural composition, non-toxicity, and superior wet and thermal properties that enable effective regulation of temperature and humidity levels compared to certain conventional materials (Tran Le et al. 2010).",
    "For example, hemp and sheep wool absorb 10 and 30 times more water than typical insulations, respectively (Platt et al. 2023)."
  ]
}